1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4 {The complex Maccutcheon Variation.} 5.
e5 h6 6. Bd2 {The main line: White can also play 6.Be3, 6.exf6 or even 6.Bh4.}
Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Qg4 {A typical move in a lot of French Defence variations.
Black now has to make an important decision: how to defend the f7 pawn?} Kf8 (
8... g6 {Is the other alternative.}) 9. Bd3 {Attacking Black's best piece!}
Nxd2 10. Kxd2 Qg5+ 11. Qxg5 hxg5 12. h4 $1 {The idea of this move is to open
the king side, because it's on that side that White has better possibilities.}
Nc6 13. f4 $5 (13. Nf3 {Looks more natural...} g4 14. Nh2 Rxh4 15. g3 {With
advantage to White.}) 13... gxf4 14. Rf1 Bd7 15. Rxf4 {Now the f7 pawn is an
objective.} Ke7 16. Rh3 {This manoeuvre is very typical in the Maccutcheon
Variation; the rook is very flexible in the third rank.} Rag8 17. Rg3 {In the
Maccutcheon, the strategy for White is to put pressure on the king side pawns,
using the heavy pieces in particular. In this case, the attack isn't enough
for White: Black has sufficient defence.} f5 $1 {Solving the problem of the
weak f7 pawn.} 18. Rg5 {It's very difficult to find a concrete plan here.
White should use a technique I called 'tormenting your opponent'. For more
information about this, take a look at the course 'Endgame Expert'.} Nd8 19.
Nh3 Nf7 20. Rg3 Rh6 21. Be2 Kf8 22. Ke3 Rgh8 23. h5 $1 {Fixing g7 as a
weakness.} Rg8 24. Ng5 Nxg5 25. Rxg5 g6 26. g4 $1 {White has his pieces best
placed, so he must open the position to take advantage of that.} gxh5 (26...
Ke7 27. hxg6 Rgxg6 28. Rxg6 Rxg6 29. gxf5 exf5 30. Rh4 $14) 27. Rxg8+ Kxg8 28.
gxh5 $14 Ba4 29. Rh4 Bxc2 30. Kf4 {White has excellent compensation for the
pawn.} Bb1 31. a3 Ba2 32. Kg5 Kg7 33. Rh2 Bb3 34. Bb5 Rh8 $2 {The decisive
mistake, allowing the pawn to advance.} (34... Bd1 {And it's difficult for
White to make progress...}) 35. h6+ Kf7 36. h7 c6 37. Bd3 Bd1 38. Rh6 Bg4 39.
Rf6+ Kg7 40. Rxe6 Rxh7 41. Re7+ 1-0

