1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4 5. e5 h6 6. Bd2 Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Qg4
g6 9. Bd3 Nxd2 10. Kxd2 c5 11. Nf3 Nc6 12. Qf4 Qa5 13. Rhb1 {Activating the
rook and threatening moves like Rb5.} cxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 {This is one
of the most critical positions in this system. Black has a better pawn
structure and White's king is in the centre. But the activity of White's
pieces and Black's weaknesses on dark squares compensate for this.} Qc7 {White
was threatening Bb5+.} (15... a6 16. Rb6 $14) (15... O-O 16. h4 $40) 16. h4 Bd7
17. Rb4 Rc8 18. Rab1 b6 19. Ba6 Rd8 20. a4 $1 {White should try to open the
position to take advantage of the activity of his pieces. If he fails to do
that, then Black has no problems - another typical scenario of the Maccutcheon
Variation.} Qc5 21. Qf4 g5 22. Qf6 Rg8 23. h5 $1 {Fixing Black weaknesses and
preventing Black's possible counterplay using the "g" file.} Bc6 24. Rd4 Qf8
25. f3 $1 {Preventing g4 followed by Rg5. Now White's plan is to clear the
rook on g8 out of the play, so that on the queen side White will have
virtually a rook up. So LET'S OPEN THE QUEEN SIDE!} Qg7 26. a5 $1 (26. Bb5 $5 {
Was a very interesting alternative...} Rc8 (26... Bxb5 27. Qxg7 Rxg7 28. axb5 {
And the "a" pawn is really weak.}) 27. Qxg7 Rxg7 28. a5 $1) 26... Qxf6 27. exf6
bxa5 28. c4 $1 {Trying to open the position completely - taking advantage of
the factor of the g8 rook...} g4 29. f4 $1 a4 30. cxd5 exd5 31. c4 $1 a3 32.
Re1+ Kd7 33. cxd5 a2 $2 {Unnecessary desperation: Black has an inferior
position without any doubt - but this simply loses a piece!} 34. dxc6+ Kxc6 {
The rest doesn't deserve any comment.} 35. Rxd8 Rxd8+ 36. Kc3 Re8 37. Ra1 Re4
38. g3 Re3+ 39. Kd4 Rxg3 40. Bc4 Kb6 41. Bxf7 Rf3 42. Rxa2 Rxf4+ 43. Ke5 Rf3
44. Be6 g3 45. f7 a5 46. Bf5 Rf2 47. f8=Q Rxa2 48. Qd6+ Kb5 49. Qd5+ Kb4 50.
Qxa2 1-0

