Kf8 9. Bd3 Nxd2 10. Kxd2 c5 11. h4 $1 c4 12. Be2 Nc6 13. Rh3 b5 14. Rg3 $1 Rg8
15. Qf4 $1 Bd7 16. Bh5 $1 {I think it's time to talk about the basic plan of
the Maccutcheon with the White pieces. The idea is to create annoying pressure
on the king side and thereby force Black to defend. This strategy explains
White's last three moves.} Be8 17. Rf3 (17. Nh3 {Is another valid alternative.}
) 17... Ke7 (17... f5 18. Bxe8 Kxe8 19. g4 Ne7 20. h5 {This probably gives
Black enough defence.}) 18. Ne2 g6 19. Bg4 h5 20. Bh3 Kd7 21. Ke1 $1 Rh8 22.
Kf1 $1 {This is another typical prophylaxis in the Maccutcheon. After this,
White has a free hand on both sides.} a5 23. Qg3 Qe7 24. Rf6 $1 Qa3 25. Qf3 {
Black's position is under pressure and here the threats Rxf7 and Qxd5 are
unavoidable.} Kc7 26. Rxf7+ $1 {The rest is easy for White.} Bxf7 27. Qxf7+ Qe7
28. Qxe6 (28. Qxg6 {Was a more accurate option...}) 28... Qxe6 29. Bxe6 Ne7 30.
Nf4 Kc6 31. Bf7 Rhf8 32. e6 b4 33. Nxg6 Nxg6 34. Bxg6 Kd6 35. Re1 Ra7 36. Bxh5
